1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,867
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambudassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambudassam

2
00:00:19,251 --> 00:00:34,813
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:35,265 --> 00:00:40,515
in the evening chanting, we go through the discourse on the highest blessings.

4
00:00:41,076 --> 00:00:45,622
So I just thought I'd use it as a sort of template and talk around it.

5
00:00:48,006 --> 00:00:53,655
It's always good to start from the sort of base of the Buddha's teachings, like where he's coming from.

6
00:00:54,417 --> 00:00:57,762
So remember, he's always coming from this position of...

7
00:00:58,890 --> 00:01:11,822
that the human being is in a state of delusion, and that the delusion isn't something culpable, it's just because we come into a situation of don't know, and from that we make this mistake.

8
00:01:12,603 --> 00:01:22,853
The mistake is, of course, to believe we're human beings, which is conventionally true, but ultimately not quite.

9
00:01:23,614 --> 00:01:24,375
Ah, come in, come in.

10
00:01:25,335 --> 00:01:28,459
I should have waited, excuse me.

11
00:01:30,969 --> 00:01:32,212
You're right on the floor, Robert.

12
00:01:39,027 --> 00:01:44,638
So the basic delusion, you might say, is this belief that we are human beings.

13
00:01:45,079 --> 00:01:50,109
And in so believing, we form a relationship with God.

14
00:01:50,647 --> 00:01:54,091
This ends your world with the world of wanting to be happy.

15
00:01:54,893 --> 00:01:58,438
And that creates a certain morality.

16
00:01:59,700 --> 00:02:08,331
If we talk about ethics as being just relationship, then as soon as we're born, we're into some sort of relationship.

17
00:02:09,052 --> 00:02:19,067
And because of this inner desire to seek happiness right from the point of being born, there is that...

18
00:02:19,739 --> 00:02:22,604
growing attitude of trying to acquire something.

19
00:02:23,246 --> 00:02:28,977
Because fundamentally, right down there at the deepest level, we know we're not safe.

20
00:02:30,901 --> 00:02:31,883
We know we're not safe.

21
00:02:32,082 --> 00:02:38,354
And so everything we're doing is to contain that fear of not being safe.

22
00:02:38,335 --> 00:02:41,901
And that becomes more obvious to you as, of course, you grow older.

23
00:02:43,123 --> 00:02:44,426
It's not so obvious to the child.

24
00:02:44,987 --> 00:02:50,397
But, of course, as soon as the child doesn't see where its mother is or father, then there's that fear comes in, you see.

25
00:02:50,979 --> 00:02:54,926
So there's that really fundamental level of not being safe.

26
00:02:56,104 --> 00:02:58,348
And so what we do is we acquire, remember.

27
00:02:58,808 --> 00:03:02,734
And acquiring things gives us some sort of feeling of safety.

28
00:03:02,753 --> 00:03:06,460
You know, your money, friends, well, anything.

29
00:03:06,539 --> 00:03:09,563
Anything you have a lot of makes you feel much more safe.

30
00:03:10,324 --> 00:03:12,707
And then, of course, you have to guard it against enemies.

31
00:03:13,109 --> 00:03:14,631
And that's where the aversion comes in.

32
00:03:14,951 --> 00:03:17,455
And if the enemy's too big, well, you've got to run for it.

33
00:03:17,435 --> 00:03:27,514
So those are your three basic attitudes that arise out of this wrong identity, the acquisitiveness, the aversion and the fear.

34
00:03:29,237 --> 00:03:36,793
So when the Buddha's teaching, he's always trying to undermine those delusions.

35
00:03:36,772 --> 00:03:40,597
And he's not trying to undermine those delusions so we end up nowhere.

36
00:03:40,997 --> 00:03:48,706
He's trying to undermine those delusions in order for us to realise or discover or rediscover perhaps what it is we truly are.

37
00:03:49,407 --> 00:03:51,750
And that's this, the unconditioned.

38
00:03:52,010 --> 00:03:54,813
So you've all noticed the new chippings on the stone there, I'm sure.

39
00:03:55,995 --> 00:04:03,903
They're a bit loud at the moment, but we're assured that over time the stone will weather and it will sort of fade into the stone.

40
00:04:03,984 --> 00:04:06,206
So it'll be rather, I think it'll be rather nice.

41
00:04:08,194 --> 00:04:18,351
And so you could say that his teachings all boil down to the unconditioned and ethics.

42
00:04:18,913 --> 00:04:27,687
Transcendence and ethics.

43
00:04:29,254 --> 00:04:33,521
And this transcendence, remember, is not just something completely separate.

44
00:04:34,081 --> 00:04:40,750
It's not as though there's a place or somewhere else that is transcendent and then we're here.

45
00:04:41,172 --> 00:04:43,654
The transcendence is right here within us now.

46
00:04:44,016 --> 00:04:48,822
So when we talk about nibbana, it's not as though we're going to create it.

47
00:04:49,242 --> 00:04:50,245
It's already here.

48
00:04:50,764 --> 00:04:51,947
It's just that we don't see it.

49
00:04:52,487 --> 00:04:57,675
And our view of life is...

50
00:04:57,654 --> 00:05:26,480
is actually clouding over our real true nature and that's what we're trying to undermine all the time in our meditation we're trying to see these three characteristics the process of desiring that's the direct psychological manifestation of this delusion that we're always trying to manipulate the world to make ourselves at least comfortable or to run away from things

51
00:05:26,461 --> 00:05:39,187
And then there's the impermanence, which we can see quite clearly around us, but it doesn't strike us until we realise actually we are impermanent as well.

52
00:05:39,252 --> 00:05:49,043
And then there's the sense of not self, which is to do basically with through the meditation of recognizing that everything we're observing is an object.

53
00:05:49,764 --> 00:05:54,067
And slowly it dawns upon us that the perceiver can't be the perceived.

54
00:05:54,088 --> 00:05:55,088
There's a gap there.

55
00:05:55,790 --> 00:05:58,752
And it also comes across when it comes to control.

56
00:05:58,793 --> 00:06:09,225
Because if you think of a soul or a self, you would presume that they are in charge of themselves, that they have their own agency.

57
00:06:09,408 --> 00:06:12,350
that they can decide how they want to be.

58
00:06:12,812 --> 00:06:19,499
But then when we find ourselves within this organism, we find we don't have that control.

59
00:06:22,101 --> 00:06:30,730
So keeping that in mind, the question that the Buddha has asked is, what are the supreme blessings?

60
00:06:31,232 --> 00:06:37,017
Now you can see that from the Buddha's point of view, blessings must be virtues.

61
00:06:36,997 --> 00:06:37,317
Right.

62
00:06:37,338 --> 00:06:38,821
So it's all about ethics.

63
00:06:39,322 --> 00:06:46,913
So it's basically trying to develop in us those beautiful virtues that all of us have to some degree or another.

64
00:06:47,454 --> 00:06:55,446
But they are, as we say, layered over by by traits that are unwholesome or unskillful.

65
00:06:55,425 --> 00:07:09,300
So here I'd like to just go through the discourse, just putting the accent on what we can develop in order to be beautiful people.

66
00:07:10,192 --> 00:07:12,274
Heart beautiful, yeah?

67
00:07:12,295 --> 00:07:15,220
Not Hollywood beautiful, yeah?

68
00:07:15,240 --> 00:07:17,944
So it starts off by saying many gods and people.

69
00:07:18,363 --> 00:07:25,694
So it was a god who had arrived to ask this question to the Buddha, this put in a mythological sense.

70
00:07:25,956 --> 00:07:33,266
But this actual discourse belongs to the early strata of the discourses.

71
00:07:33,286 --> 00:07:37,632
So it goes back, really, back to his early teachings, you might say.

72
00:07:39,470 --> 00:07:44,098
So he says not to associate with fools, but associating with the wise.

73
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:52,913
So if you look at your past life, the question would arise is, you know, how many daft relationships have I had?

74
00:07:54,235 --> 00:07:54,677
How many?

75
00:07:55,298 --> 00:07:57,982
And what has awakened me out of that?

76
00:07:58,543 --> 00:08:00,204
And what are my relationships now?

77
00:08:00,745 --> 00:08:08,235
So if our purpose, if our purpose is to liberate us from suffering, the Buddha says that good companionship is absolutely crucial.

78
00:08:10,399 --> 00:08:15,365
Who you mix with, who you associate with are going to have an effect on you.

79
00:08:16,560 --> 00:08:20,149
So he's basically saying those who are, you know, stay with the ones who are wise.

80
00:08:21,411 --> 00:08:25,762
But here, this wise, you have to read it a little bit.

81
00:08:25,841 --> 00:08:27,586
It's not worldly wise, remember.

82
00:08:27,766 --> 00:08:36,105
I mean, that's included, but it's more to do with spiritual companions because he's always looking to liberate us from our delusions.

83
00:08:36,996 --> 00:08:40,621
and to honour those who are worthy of honour.

84
00:08:41,724 --> 00:08:58,386
And so our heroes, the people whom we see as people who are paragons, the people whom we can measure ourselves against.

85
00:08:59,808 --> 00:09:03,274
Now, it's funny, when I was a child...

86
00:09:04,739 --> 00:09:08,582
you know, being brought up in a very religious Catholic family.

87
00:09:09,163 --> 00:09:11,706
My mother was very religious, and so was my father.

88
00:09:12,847 --> 00:09:16,692
The actual reading books we were given were the Book of the Saints.

89
00:09:18,393 --> 00:09:23,778
And I'm just wondering, how many children these days get a Book of the Saints for Christmas?

90
00:09:25,581 --> 00:09:30,426
Even if it's on a stick, you know, on their computer.

91
00:09:30,710 --> 00:09:39,072
So very early on, my heroes were these saints, you know, people who'd done these amazing things and were holy, you know.

92
00:09:40,155 --> 00:09:42,863
They weren't pop stars or anything like that.

93
00:09:44,985 --> 00:09:52,221
So our question is to ourselves, well, who do I praise?

94
00:09:52,482 --> 00:09:57,894
Who are the people in my life whom I see as worthy to praise?

95
00:09:58,196 --> 00:10:02,826
And this should bring out a feeling of wanting to be like them.

96
00:10:02,806 --> 00:10:19,514
When, as a child, I would read these saints who've done these amazing things, there would be an admiration arise in me, and somewhere within me, I would want to be like them.

97
00:10:20,034 --> 00:10:35,674
And, of course, you would still get that sort of religious approach in the East, especially in places like Burma, which have remained fairly, well, up until fairly recently, maybe, fairly religious in their society.

98
00:10:36,416 --> 00:10:44,466
So it would always, you know, children would always be taught about all the saints, the early Buddhist saints and the Buddha himself, you see.

99
00:10:45,086 --> 00:10:47,089
And they would be their heroes, you see.

100
00:10:48,993 --> 00:10:55,932
So it's good just to contemplate who do we see as our heroes.

101
00:10:57,397 --> 00:11:00,182
Then he goes on to say living in a suitable place.

102
00:11:01,384 --> 00:11:09,597
So that's, you know, he's like the Buddha is not just simply up in the air somewhere with all these wonderful virtues.

103
00:11:10,119 --> 00:11:14,365
He is grounded and he's talking about living in a suitable place.

104
00:11:14,746 --> 00:11:20,636
And again, a suitable place would would be somewhere where you can feel you you can practice.

105
00:11:20,616 --> 00:11:25,910
And that's not always possible, of course, but at least one can do one's best.

106
00:11:26,371 --> 00:11:29,801
But it's interesting that he should put that down as a blessing.

107
00:11:30,261 --> 00:11:34,272
Remember that all these are meant to be fortunate blessings.

108
00:11:35,500 --> 00:11:37,461
And to have done good deeds in the past.

109
00:11:37,903 --> 00:11:49,778
So this is a reminder that we are bearing the fruits or suffering the fruits of things that we've done in the past.

110
00:11:49,798 --> 00:11:51,139
And there's no way out of that.

111
00:11:51,178 --> 00:11:53,402
You've got to stay with it.

112
00:11:53,763 --> 00:11:57,407
But hopefully they've been very good and now we're very happy.

113
00:11:59,412 --> 00:12:02,216
And then he goes on to say, write the right aspirations.

114
00:12:02,697 --> 00:12:07,365
So what are our aspirations?

115
00:12:08,246 --> 00:12:13,876
How do we see ourselves guiding towards what future?

116
00:12:14,059 --> 00:12:16,743
Because that's a guiding light within our lives.

117
00:12:17,364 --> 00:12:22,269
If you don't have somewhere to go, then you might end up anywhere.

118
00:12:23,932 --> 00:12:26,816
So spiritually speaking, our aim is quite direct.

119
00:12:26,895 --> 00:12:33,222
It's trying to, first of all, purify the heart and to get in touch with this unconditioned nature within us.

120
00:12:34,424 --> 00:12:39,431
And not to be caught up with sort of false hopes, false ideas of what we can do.

121
00:12:40,312 --> 00:12:41,974
So an aspiration.

122
00:12:42,544 --> 00:12:54,307
The big aspiration, of course, in Buddhism is to become a Bodhisattva, which is rather the big aspiration is to become a fully self-awakened Buddha.

123
00:12:54,947 --> 00:12:56,691
And we have a special word for these people.

124
00:12:56,711 --> 00:12:59,897
They're called Bodhisattvas, you see, Bodhisattvas in the Pali.

125
00:13:00,437 --> 00:13:03,945
So that would be an aspiration.

126
00:13:05,258 --> 00:13:10,905
There was a monk called Ananda Maitreya, very famous in Sri Lanka.

127
00:13:11,407 --> 00:13:15,011
And when he died, thousands came out for his funeral.

128
00:13:15,611 --> 00:13:24,684
And he had been to Khandaboda, which is where I myself had trained, and had practiced with the Mahasi himself there.

129
00:13:25,306 --> 00:13:41,525
And it is said that when somebody goes through the process of insight in order to enter the first path and fruit, just before you go in there, ancient or earlier aspirations arise.

130
00:13:41,505 --> 00:13:55,667
come up you see and he remembered making this aspiration to become a fully self-awakened Buddha and he said he could remember the faces of the two main disciples Moggallana and Sariputta but not of the Buddha unfortunately

131
00:13:56,052 --> 00:14:08,628
And it stopped him moving, you see, because what the tradition says is that to become a fully self-awakened Buddha, you have to have all the virtues ready, all the perfections ready.

132
00:14:08,668 --> 00:14:12,153
And then when you're born, you go through it in one lifetime.

133
00:14:12,774 --> 00:14:20,524
And I presume that's why you end up being a fairly good teacher, because you've actually experienced the whole process in one lifetime.

134
00:14:20,504 --> 00:14:22,587
Which is not necessary otherwise.

135
00:14:23,328 --> 00:14:26,173
So he remembered that and he couldn't go through.

136
00:14:26,214 --> 00:14:29,961
And he reinforced his commitment, as far as I know.

137
00:14:30,100 --> 00:14:31,222
Reinforced his commitment.

138
00:14:33,707 --> 00:14:39,437
We have another example of that, of Ajahn Mun, whose biography was written by Ajahn Mahabua.

139
00:14:39,557 --> 00:14:40,840
It's a great old story.

140
00:14:41,461 --> 00:14:42,342
And...

141
00:14:42,677 --> 00:14:46,604
He remembered making this vow to become a fully self-awakened Buddha.

142
00:14:47,085 --> 00:14:50,110
And then he realized it was just so difficult that he renounced it.

143
00:14:51,192 --> 00:14:55,118
It just meant for being an ordinary, fully enlightened being.

144
00:14:58,624 --> 00:15:01,048
So these are our aspirations.

145
00:15:01,087 --> 00:15:02,389
What's your aspiration?

146
00:15:02,649 --> 00:15:04,212
What is your aspiration?

147
00:15:06,320 --> 00:15:07,522
And then again, he's grounded.

148
00:15:07,542 --> 00:15:12,769
He wants us to have great learning and craft depending on what we do in life.

149
00:15:13,450 --> 00:15:15,894
Right livelihood is right there in the Eightfold Path.

150
00:15:17,936 --> 00:15:26,808
So right livelihood is where you are sharing your gifts for the benefit of society as a whole.

151
00:15:26,788 --> 00:15:35,803
So even if the job is the most menial, it's irrelevant because it's a way in which you share what you have for the benefit of others.

152
00:15:36,144 --> 00:15:38,748
And therefore, there's a sense of service to it.

153
00:15:39,789 --> 00:15:46,221
And that undermines things like boredom and hopelessness and all the things that might come up in a work situation.

154
00:15:47,022 --> 00:15:50,147
So that's there also deep in his teachings.

155
00:15:50,397 --> 00:15:55,346
Can I just suggest you open that back door and the window in the corridor.

156
00:15:55,746 --> 00:15:56,729
Just get a bit of air through.

157
00:15:57,068 --> 00:16:01,056
It's all right if you fall asleep.

158
00:16:01,076 --> 00:16:02,197
It would be terrible if I did.

159
00:16:04,182 --> 00:16:06,886
In mid-sentence.

160
00:16:09,263 --> 00:16:12,787
And then to be well disciplined.

161
00:16:12,988 --> 00:16:15,471
That's a word we don't particularly like these days, discipline.

162
00:16:16,772 --> 00:16:19,174
We usually think of it as being enforced upon us.

163
00:16:19,875 --> 00:16:22,698
But it's something, of course, that we have to develop ourselves.

164
00:16:23,159 --> 00:16:28,166
So it's just making sure, for instance, that we do do that morning meditation.

165
00:16:28,787 --> 00:16:30,528
I'm not going to quiz you.

166
00:16:30,509 --> 00:16:32,291
And things like that.

167
00:16:32,591 --> 00:16:33,451
And well-trained.

168
00:16:34,113 --> 00:16:34,874
Well-trained.

169
00:16:35,414 --> 00:16:39,298
When I was in Burma once, there was this grandfather.

170
00:16:39,318 --> 00:16:41,981
He had his little boy with him, his little grandson.

171
00:16:42,822 --> 00:16:49,811
And he didn't say, you know, we've taken him to school, we're having him educated.

172
00:16:50,532 --> 00:16:52,634
He said, this is my little grandson.

173
00:16:53,075 --> 00:16:54,356
He has to be trained.

174
00:16:57,980 --> 00:16:59,081
Very different approach.

175
00:16:59,922 --> 00:17:26,030
speaking ah yes well speech is the big one because again it's in the eightfold path right speech and the buddha simply asks us to to be timely you know to say it at the right time to say what is true or at least not not to be not to be purposely false to be gentle in our speech and to make sure it's beneficial right so sometimes it's best not to speak yeah

176
00:17:26,752 --> 00:17:28,736
And always coming from the heart of goodwill.

177
00:17:29,136 --> 00:17:29,998
The heart of goodwill.

178
00:17:32,521 --> 00:17:34,644
So remember, these are all supreme blessings.

179
00:17:35,125 --> 00:17:40,795
They're not only, I mean, they are something we develop, but they're also a consequence of good practice.

180
00:17:41,896 --> 00:17:43,619
And virtue makes us happy.

181
00:17:44,961 --> 00:17:47,125
And then he's looking at relationships.

182
00:17:47,144 --> 00:17:51,511
So attendance on one's mother and father, looking after one's spouse and children.

183
00:17:52,066 --> 00:17:56,313
So remember, these are advices giving to lay people.

184
00:17:57,976 --> 00:18:01,161
And then he talks about work which is not stressful.

185
00:18:02,323 --> 00:18:04,405
You can translate the word as not stressful.

186
00:18:04,946 --> 00:18:08,492
So even in those days, seemingly, they had stressful work.

187
00:18:10,276 --> 00:18:12,640
So obviously, something that's not new.

188
00:18:13,395 --> 00:18:15,199
Then comes this generosity.

189
00:18:15,240 --> 00:18:20,068
Generosity, whenever he was speaking to lay people, he always began with generosity.

190
00:18:20,910 --> 00:18:24,297
It's the simplest of virtues to exercise.

191
00:18:24,998 --> 00:18:30,087
He pointed out that you can even be generous to a thief who's just stolen your stuff.

192
00:18:31,974 --> 00:18:41,528
And there's this virtuous circle of gratitude, generosity and renunciation.

193
00:18:42,368 --> 00:18:51,080
So when you contemplate how much you've been given in this life, I think you very quickly come to the conclusion that there's no way you can repay it.

194
00:18:51,279 --> 00:19:01,993
If you go back to your childhood, to your education, to your health system, the whole lot, when you look backwards, you've been given so much that it's impossible to find a way of repaying it.

195
00:19:02,253 --> 00:19:15,009
Now, what this does is it puts a certain desire in you, almost a demand to try and repay at least some of it through a process of generosity.

196
00:19:14,990 --> 00:19:22,000
Now, every time you're generous, you're giving away something that belongs to you, which you could have personally enjoyed.

197
00:19:22,039 --> 00:19:22,961
It could be your wealth.

198
00:19:23,041 --> 00:19:24,143
It could be your time.

199
00:19:24,163 --> 00:19:26,807
And you've got to give that away.

200
00:19:26,846 --> 00:19:29,089
And there's your renunciation.

201
00:19:29,391 --> 00:19:34,298
So what you are holding on to, you've got to give for the benefit of others.

202
00:19:34,446 --> 00:19:43,637
And it's a sort of difficult area because to be truly generous, to know that you're being truly, it has to hurt a bit.

203
00:19:44,378 --> 00:19:49,704
See, you've not given away something that just pinches you.

204
00:19:50,125 --> 00:19:52,288
And that's the process of renunciation.

205
00:19:52,708 --> 00:19:57,094
And the whole of the spiritual life, you know, eventually is renunciation.

206
00:19:57,594 --> 00:19:59,536
Because remember, our problem is acquisition.

207
00:19:59,596 --> 00:20:02,579
We're always trying to hold on to things, keep things.

208
00:20:04,315 --> 00:20:09,788
So that's an important virtue to consider, you see.

209
00:20:10,630 --> 00:20:13,616
And then living according to the Dharma, that's pretty straightforward.

210
00:20:14,078 --> 00:20:15,923
And then he sort of recaps.

211
00:20:16,523 --> 00:20:19,771
Remember, this is a poem, so it's a bit all over the place.

212
00:20:20,192 --> 00:20:22,137
And then looking after one's relatives.

213
00:20:23,501 --> 00:20:27,009
Then he goes on to say, behaving in a way that is blameless.

214
00:20:28,252 --> 00:20:34,807
So here you have these qualities of shame and dread.

215
00:20:35,630 --> 00:20:41,442
So now in the Buddha's understanding, these two happen to be guardians of society.

216
00:20:41,423 --> 00:20:54,182
Because if you do stuff which everybody sees as shameful and you're not ashamed, then obviously there's not much to stop you doing things which are, frankly, could be evil.

217
00:20:55,684 --> 00:21:00,613
And not worrying about consequences of doing something.

218
00:21:00,593 --> 00:21:19,753
So if in a society, I mean, this is, shall we say, some of the problems that we're having even now because of the reduction of the police force, that people who are committing crimes, low-level crimes, stealing and all that sort of stuff, are just simply getting away with it and not being followed up.

219
00:21:19,974 --> 00:21:27,202
So that means that, generally speaking, the message goes out, you know, you may as well do it because it's a win-win situation.

220
00:21:27,462 --> 00:21:27,563
Yeah.

221
00:21:28,977 --> 00:21:42,980
So again, that loss of dread of consequences and a sort of loss of inner dignity about your own moral stance means that you start doing things which are basically immoral.

222
00:21:44,561 --> 00:21:47,948
So those are things that...

223
00:21:50,257 --> 00:21:51,398
We have to ponder.

224
00:21:51,638 --> 00:22:03,556
So if we find ourselves in a situation where we feel there's a moral dilemma there, an ethical question, you see, just ask yourself, well, if I do it, how am I going to feel?

225
00:22:04,096 --> 00:22:06,240
How am I going to live with it?

226
00:22:07,060 --> 00:22:15,032
And that's one way of seeing that these two mental states, shame and dread, are actually guarding us.

227
00:22:15,093 --> 00:22:16,634
They're guarding us from doing something.

228
00:22:19,686 --> 00:22:27,959
So abstaining from what is unwholesome, avoiding immoral actions, and then, of course, a very difficult one, restraint from intoxicants.

229
00:22:29,422 --> 00:22:31,464
So they had problems even in those times.

230
00:22:31,984 --> 00:22:33,387
Restraint from intoxicants.

231
00:22:34,348 --> 00:22:35,391
And being heedful.

232
00:22:35,810 --> 00:22:40,057
Heedful, that word is very much one of his favourite words.

233
00:22:40,657 --> 00:22:43,061
In fact, it's the one he...

234
00:22:43,041 --> 00:22:44,949
on his dying breath.

235
00:22:46,093 --> 00:22:48,823
You know, all compounded things are impermanent.

236
00:22:49,365 --> 00:22:51,452
Strive diligently for your liberation.

237
00:22:51,634 --> 00:22:53,862
That's your acpamado.

238
00:22:58,988 --> 00:23:02,211
And then respectful, humble.

239
00:23:02,490 --> 00:23:05,413
Humble is a word that gets a bit confused for us.

240
00:23:05,653 --> 00:23:08,396
It feels like you're doing yourself down or something.

241
00:23:08,958 --> 00:23:12,881
But it's really just seeing yourself as you are, being humble.

242
00:23:14,563 --> 00:23:15,503
Being content.

243
00:23:16,224 --> 00:23:23,852
Now, that's a big one, content, because content suggests no more of those unwholesome desires.

244
00:23:24,092 --> 00:23:26,835
And it's a quality of the Buddha, contentment.

245
00:23:26,815 --> 00:23:35,895
When he's asked, when he's asked, or when he, that's right, somebody says to him, this teaching you're giving us, this practice is very difficult.

246
00:23:36,557 --> 00:23:40,487
And he said, well, it is, he says, but in the end, you achieve nibbana.

247
00:23:41,450 --> 00:23:45,499
And the other, and the questioner says, nibbana, so what?

248
00:23:45,479 --> 00:23:56,621
He says, well, he says, when you get there, he says, you are, you are happy and with, you are, you are content and with it happy.

249
00:23:58,724 --> 00:24:01,529
You are content and with it happy.

250
00:24:01,509 --> 00:24:09,721
And that contentment means you have no attaching desire, no grasping desire.

251
00:24:09,740 --> 00:24:11,603
It's not as though the Buddha doesn't have desire.

252
00:24:11,623 --> 00:24:13,384
He has desire to help people, for the start.

253
00:24:13,986 --> 00:24:19,594
But he doesn't have that sort of grasping desire, that sticky desire.

254
00:24:24,098 --> 00:24:25,340
Humble...

255
00:24:27,463 --> 00:24:31,568
And then there's gratitude comes up there.

256
00:24:31,628 --> 00:24:32,869
So we've discussed that.

257
00:24:33,310 --> 00:24:35,153
Listening to the Dharma at the right time.

258
00:24:35,752 --> 00:24:42,922
So there are three levels of understanding that he points out.

259
00:24:42,942 --> 00:24:49,489
The first one is the understanding you come to when you hear something or in our case also read something.

260
00:24:50,531 --> 00:24:57,871
And then there's the understanding that comes when it becomes your own personal intellectual understanding, your own intellectual property, you might say.

261
00:24:58,833 --> 00:25:06,211
And then finally, it's brought about as a real experience through your practice.

262
00:25:07,458 --> 00:25:17,212
Daily practice, practice in your daily life, doesn't matter what you're doing, but it's brought into a sense of this is real for me, it's not just an intellectual understanding.

263
00:25:18,154 --> 00:25:25,246
So it is important, I think, to keep feeding ourselves with some Dharma.

264
00:25:25,266 --> 00:25:34,359
It doesn't matter how much, it's up to you to decide how much, but as you know, there's masses now on the websites, up on the web there,

265
00:25:34,896 --> 00:25:40,083
And listening to a talk, reading a book or something, even if it's only a little bit.

266
00:25:40,103 --> 00:25:41,865
And to find something that inspires you.

267
00:25:43,106 --> 00:25:44,167
I think that's important.

268
00:25:44,888 --> 00:25:47,872
So it's listening to the Dharma, he says, at the right time.

269
00:25:47,932 --> 00:25:50,935
I suppose at the right time means not while you're eating.

270
00:25:53,838 --> 00:25:59,065
It's like, I find a time when you can actually devote your entire attention to it.

271
00:26:00,125 --> 00:26:00,705
Patience.

272
00:26:01,207 --> 00:26:02,750
So patience is a big one too.

273
00:26:02,770 --> 00:26:07,441
He talks about it being the highest form of ascetic practice, patience.

274
00:26:08,301 --> 00:26:11,710
Asceticism has a sort of bad word for itself.

275
00:26:11,730 --> 00:26:17,121
It's like you're making yourself suffer to see how much you can bear.

276
00:26:17,911 --> 00:26:23,880
But here, of course, it means the asceticism of letting go, of not reacting, of non-reaction.

277
00:26:24,601 --> 00:26:41,227
And the big example he gives there, he says, you know, if somebody were to come and saw you apart or machete you apart in bits and pieces, and if at any time hatred should arise in your heart, he says, you're not a disciple of mine.

278
00:26:41,247 --> 00:26:45,993
And I once said this to a group and somebody said, yeah, but the Buddha had a great sense of humor.

279
00:26:46,682 --> 00:26:50,066
I think he actually meant it.

280
00:26:51,027 --> 00:26:52,028
Anyway, that's patience.

281
00:26:52,107 --> 00:27:02,777
So all the time you'll find, you know, we're always impatient because the problem with attachment, remember, is a sense of frustration that you get when you're not getting what you want.

282
00:27:03,137 --> 00:27:16,690
So even if the train is late or it arrives late or the post hasn't come or you get to the shop and somebody's taken the last piece of bread, there's always that sort of, there's always got frustration, people who don't do what you want them to do.

283
00:27:16,670 --> 00:27:44,803
so this patience has a real role to play in our lives easily spoken to that's a bit difficult too we don't like to be told anyway that we're doing something wrong that's always a bit of a thump to our pride but just the ability to acknowledge yeah I shouldn't have done that and an easy way of asking for forgiveness just saying sorry

284
00:27:45,339 --> 00:27:47,545
Some people find that extraordinarily difficult.

285
00:27:50,109 --> 00:27:54,179
But it's a relief to the heart because sometimes you do make mistakes.

286
00:27:54,199 --> 00:27:58,407
Sometimes completely unconsciously.

287
00:27:59,509 --> 00:28:03,618
And then you're blamed and you just say, fine, I'm sorry.

288
00:28:07,176 --> 00:28:08,298
Where are we?

289
00:28:09,298 --> 00:28:09,920
Easily spoken to.

290
00:28:10,280 --> 00:28:11,701
Seeing spiritual teachers.

291
00:28:13,044 --> 00:28:18,170
Yeah, that's I mean, well, that's part of listening to listening to or seeing people on the web and whatnot.

292
00:28:19,451 --> 00:28:21,753
That's also part of our practice, really.

293
00:28:21,773 --> 00:28:23,955
But then there's discussing Dharma at the right time.

294
00:28:24,116 --> 00:28:29,623
So that's the bit where really you begin to make it your own.

295
00:28:29,873 --> 00:28:38,781
Personal knowledge is when you can actually discuss it with somebody, when you actually talk about it, rather than just having it as a passive reception.

296
00:28:39,403 --> 00:28:42,566
And that's when you really begin to make it your own understanding.

297
00:28:50,354 --> 00:28:54,817
It's interesting, there was a passage there of Bahia of the Barcloth.

298
00:28:54,950 --> 00:28:56,531
But he was an ascetic.

299
00:28:56,592 --> 00:29:00,576
He only wore cloth made out of bark, which to us sounds ridiculous.

300
00:29:00,676 --> 00:29:04,602
But in those days, with certain trees, you can beat them and they turn into cloth.

301
00:29:05,823 --> 00:29:09,847
And it seems as though he'd heard about the Buddha and he came to see him.

302
00:29:10,808 --> 00:29:16,256
And he says to the Buddha, look, can you give me the teaching?

303
00:29:16,395 --> 00:29:17,396
The Buddha's on alms round.

304
00:29:17,517 --> 00:29:22,222
And he says, well, yes, I'll just finish off my alms round and then we can talk, you see.

305
00:29:22,844 --> 00:29:23,826
And he says, look, I'm dead.

306
00:29:23,948 --> 00:29:24,650
I'm really old.

307
00:29:24,911 --> 00:29:26,134
I could die any minute.

308
00:29:26,174 --> 00:29:28,983
So the Buddha has pity on him.

309
00:29:29,666 --> 00:29:33,157
And right there and there, he gives him this teaching.

310
00:29:33,374 --> 00:29:35,678
It's a very famous teaching.

311
00:29:35,738 --> 00:29:37,420
It says, in the hearing, there's only the hearing.

312
00:29:37,440 --> 00:29:39,262
In the seeing, there's only the seeing.

313
00:29:39,923 --> 00:29:42,689
In the knowing, there's only the knowing.

314
00:29:42,929 --> 00:29:44,592
There's a bit more to it, but I can't remember.

315
00:29:45,272 --> 00:29:48,017
And he becomes fully liberated right there and then.

316
00:29:48,637 --> 00:29:50,280
And the Buddha gave titles to people.

317
00:29:50,401 --> 00:29:54,067
For instance, Sariputta was called the general of the Dharma.

318
00:29:54,488 --> 00:29:59,095
So the title for Bahia was the one who became enlightened the quickest.

319
00:29:59,750 --> 00:30:01,733
He made it there and then.

320
00:30:01,775 --> 00:30:06,384
Anyway, as fate would have it, he was finally gored to death by a cow.

321
00:30:08,951 --> 00:30:09,873
It's a little story.

322
00:30:09,992 --> 00:30:11,355
So he was right.

323
00:30:11,395 --> 00:30:12,679
He didn't have long to go.

324
00:30:17,619 --> 00:30:20,884
The next one is simplicity.

325
00:30:20,924 --> 00:30:28,296
So the old monastic way of talking about that was poverty.

326
00:30:29,198 --> 00:30:35,267
Poverty now has a sort of meaning of not having enough to eat, etc., etc.

327
00:30:36,067 --> 00:30:38,192
But it's more to do with simplicity.

328
00:30:38,913 --> 00:30:40,454
What do you actually need?

329
00:30:40,434 --> 00:30:45,261
So that's something we can ask ourselves, especially with all this climate stuff going on.

330
00:30:45,682 --> 00:30:46,683
How much do we actually need?

331
00:30:46,763 --> 00:30:48,406
How much hot water do we use?

332
00:30:48,606 --> 00:30:52,051
It's like drawing ourselves down to a level of sufficiency.

333
00:30:52,531 --> 00:30:53,834
What is sufficient?

334
00:30:57,619 --> 00:30:59,702
Living spiritually, that's pretty straightforward.

335
00:30:59,762 --> 00:31:01,525
Insight into the noble truths.

336
00:31:02,326 --> 00:31:04,450
And finally, the experience of nirvana.

337
00:31:04,549 --> 00:31:08,855
So that's obviously something that would be a great blessing.

338
00:31:09,712 --> 00:31:11,194
And then there's an ending.

339
00:31:11,214 --> 00:31:18,263
He said, those whose minds does not wander when tempted by the things of this world, they are without grief.

340
00:31:18,805 --> 00:31:19,665
They're without grief.

341
00:31:19,685 --> 00:31:20,507
See, no sorrow.

342
00:31:21,648 --> 00:31:23,211
One can let things go, you see.

343
00:31:24,692 --> 00:31:35,906
Even, you know, people who are close to us who die, to be able to just let that go, not to get into the cycle of grief again.

344
00:31:35,886 --> 00:31:57,117
uh confusing grief with love so every time your grief disappears you feel you're losing their love you see whereas you might be sorry you might have a certain sorrow especially if they died young or or unfortunately uh but to just accept their karma you know we're we're heir to our karma we own our karma and so on and so forth

345
00:31:59,393 --> 00:32:01,535
And we're pure and serene of heart, you see.

346
00:32:02,415 --> 00:32:05,858
When the mind doesn't get tempted by the world, it's pure, it's serene.

347
00:32:05,898 --> 00:32:08,162
It finds this inner serenity.

348
00:32:09,403 --> 00:32:12,226
And those who follow these instructions, they're not overwhelmed.

349
00:32:12,286 --> 00:32:14,448
They're not hijacked any time.

350
00:32:15,167 --> 00:32:20,854
So it's this effort to develop these virtues which run alongside awareness.

351
00:32:22,015 --> 00:32:28,961
The more you're aware in the proper way, right awareness, the more these virtues naturally develop.

352
00:32:29,059 --> 00:32:32,545
So wherever they go, they are safe from spiritual danger.

353
00:32:33,586 --> 00:32:41,518
You're not safe from being run over, but you're safe from spiritual danger.

354
00:32:42,298 --> 00:32:45,544
And so these are the highest blessings.

355
00:32:45,825 --> 00:32:47,046
So that's a discourse.

356
00:32:47,105 --> 00:32:54,718
It's not comprehensive, but it gives us some idea of how to reflect upon things.

357
00:32:54,778 --> 00:32:55,759
That's all, you know.

358
00:32:58,726 --> 00:33:05,326
And I thought I would finally end off with Brexit.

359
00:33:08,007 --> 00:33:10,309
I can't give a talk without the word Brexit in it.

360
00:33:10,990 --> 00:33:12,172
I could leave it there.

361
00:33:15,816 --> 00:33:20,903
We're all very upset.

362
00:33:20,923 --> 00:33:23,164
Just I came across something which might be of interest to you.

363
00:33:23,665 --> 00:33:31,095
Edmund Burke, who was a philosopher and an MP, he was the one who...

364
00:33:31,075 --> 00:33:38,851
who expressed his very famous statement, all that is necessary for the triumph of evil is that good men do nothing.

365
00:33:38,871 --> 00:33:41,115
He's well known for that, you see.

366
00:33:41,135 --> 00:33:48,932
But he was an MP for Bristol and he was only one session because they got rid of him after that.

367
00:33:49,756 --> 00:33:51,759
And he went into another easy place.

368
00:33:52,440 --> 00:33:55,564
But this is what he says of an MP at Parliament.

369
00:33:55,625 --> 00:34:02,453
And I think it's sort of, you know, in the context of what's happening today, it's something to reflect on.

370
00:34:03,035 --> 00:34:17,315
He says, by the way, he's considered to be the founder of modern conservatism and the founder of the party system and to have established what a Member of Parliament is, right?

371
00:34:18,190 --> 00:34:32,447
So he says here, he says, Parliament is not a Congress of ambassadors from different and hostile interests, which interests each must maintain as an agent and an advocate against other agents and advocates.

372
00:34:33,329 --> 00:34:40,737
But Parliament is the deliberative assembly of one nation with one interest, that of the whole.

373
00:34:41,427 --> 00:34:51,322
where not local purposes, not local prejudices ought to guide, but the general good, resulting from the general reason of the whole.

374
00:34:52,144 --> 00:34:59,617
You choose a member indeed, but when you've chosen him, he is not a member of Bristol, but he is a member of Parliament.

375
00:35:00,418 --> 00:35:02,081
Ah, it's a strong statement, huh?

376
00:35:03,804 --> 00:35:05,106
So I thought I'd leave it there.

377
00:35:06,554 --> 00:35:11,420
Just a clarity, because there's lots of confusion about parliamentary democracy.

378
00:35:12,461 --> 00:35:13,483
Yeah, send it to Boris.

379
00:35:14,423 --> 00:35:15,806
Well, now you've got to be careful, you see.

380
00:35:16,427 --> 00:35:17,688
Some people like Boris.

381
00:35:18,128 --> 00:35:19,771
So we're not taking sides here.

382
00:35:19,811 --> 00:35:26,099
I was just clarifying what an MP is supposed to be.

383
00:35:26,119 --> 00:35:26,840
Send it to them all.

384
00:35:26,956 --> 00:35:56,523
well that might do I'm sure they know it it's not that they don't know it they probably read Edmund Burke I've only read the statement oh I think they know it they just decide not to behave like that so I hope my words have been of some assistance that they have not caused even greater confusion and that by your constant effort you will indeed become liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later

